05697nam a22007695i 9780231549950DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018060641  a97802315499507 a10.7312/sinc192762doi  a(DE-B1597)525835  a(OCoLC)1082329909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aN6537.R27bR64 2019 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.222300aRobert Rauschenberg :bAn Oral History /ced. by Sara Sinclair, Peter Bearman, Mary Marshall Clark. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :bB&W photographs with color insert  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Columbia Oral History Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tReader’s Guide -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1. Small World -- t2. Collaborations -- t3. 381 Lafayette Street -- t4. Captiva -- t5. Travelogue -- t6. Rauschenberg Overseas Culture Interchange [ROCI] -- t7. Curating and Installations -- t8. An Expanding American Art Market -- t9. No One Wanted It to End -- tNetwork Diagrams -- tNarrators -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRobert Rauschenberg (1925–2008) was a breaker of boundaries and a consummate collaborator. He used silk-screen prints to reflect on American promise and failure, melded sculpture and painting in works called combines, and collaborated with engineers and scientists to challenge our thinking about art. Through collaborations with John Cage, Merce Cunningham, and others, Rauschenberg bridged the music, dance, and visual-art worlds, inventing a new art for the last half of the twentieth century.Robert Rauschenberg is a work of collaborative oral biography that tells the story of one of the twentieth century’s great artists through a series of interviews with key figures in his life—family, friends, former lovers, professional associates, studio assistants, and collaborators. The oral historian Sara Sinclair artfully puts the narrators’ reminiscences in conversation, with a focus on the relationship between Rauschenberg’s intense social life and his art. The book opens with a prologue by Rauschenberg’s sister and then shifts to New York City’s 1950s and ’60s art scene, populated by the luminaries of abstract expressionism. It follows Rauschenberg’s eventual move to Florida’s Captiva Island and his trips across the globe, illuminating his inner life and its effect on his and others’ art.The narrators share their views on Rauschenberg’s work, explore the curatorial thinking behind exhibitions of his art, and reflect on the impact of the influx of money into the contemporary art market. Included are artists famous in the own right, such as Laurie Anderson and Brice Marden, as well as art-world insiders and lesser-known figures who were part of Rauschenberg’s inner circle. Beyond considering Rauschenberg as an artist, this book reveals him as a man embedded in a series of art worlds over the course of a long and rich life, demonstrating the complex interaction of business and personal, public and private in the creation of great art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArtistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh1 aBearman, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Mary Marshall, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSinclair, Sara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2019z9783110605747oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBoo